---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "How does OWASP Dependency-Check find vulnerabilities?",
    answer: "It analyzes your project's dependencies, extracts CPE (Common Platform Enumeration) identifiers, and cross-references them against the NVD (National Vulnerability Database) CVE feed. It uses evidence collectors for file names, manifest data, and JAR manifests to identify component versions, then matches against known CVE records."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the NVD API key and why do I need it?",
    answer: "The NVD switched to an API key model in 2023. Without a key, database updates are rate-limited to 5 requests per 30 seconds, making initial downloads very slow (30–60 minutes). With a free NVD API key the limit rises to 50 requests per 30 seconds, reducing update time to under 5 minutes. Register free at nvd.nist.gov/developers/request-an-api-key."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I suppress false positives in OWASP Dependency-Check?",
    answer: "Create a suppression XML file and pass it via --suppression or the Maven/Gradle suppressionFile config. Each entry specifies a CVE ID and a file path glob or CPE. You can suppress by SHA-1 hash for precise targeting. Add a notes attribute explaining why the finding is a false positive to maintain an audit trail."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between OWASP Dependency-Check and Snyk?",
    answer: "OWASP Dependency-Check is open-source, free, and works offline with a local NVD copy — ideal for air-gapped environments and Java/Maven shops. Snyk is a commercial SaaS platform (free tier available) with a curated database, automated fix PRs, container scanning, and better false-positive rates. DC requires more tuning; Snyk is more turnkey."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I integrate OWASP Dependency-Check with a Maven build?",
    answer: "Add the org.owasp:dependency-check-maven plugin to your pom.xml and bind it to the verify phase. Set failBuildOnCVSS to 7 to block builds with high/critical issues. Run 'mvn verify' or specifically 'mvn dependency-check:check'. Configure the NVD API key via the nvdApiKey parameter or as a Maven property."
  },
  {
    question: "What ecosystems and languages does OWASP Dependency-Check support?",
    answer: "OWASP Dependency-Check supports Java (JAR/WAR/EAR), .NET assemblies, Node.js (package-lock.json, yarn.lock), Python (requirements.txt, setup.py), Ruby (Gemfile.lock), PHP (composer.lock), Swift/Cocoa, Go (go.sum), and more. Java/Maven has the best support; some ecosystems require experimental analyzers to be enabled."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="OWASP Dependency-Check: Setup, CI Integration & Report Guide"
  description="OWASP Dependency-Check setup guide for Java, Node.js, .NET. Maven/Gradle/CLI usage, HTML reports, CI/CD integration, NVD API key setup, and false positive suppression."
  tool="OWASP Dependency-Check, NVD, CVE scanning, Maven plugin, Gradle, CI vulnerability scanner"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "OWASP Dependency-Check: Setup, CI Integration & Report Guide",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/owasp-dependency-check",
    "description": "OWASP Dependency-Check setup guide for Java, Node.js, .NET. Maven/Gradle/CLI usage, HTML reports, CI/CD integration, NVD API key setup, and false positive suppression.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">OWASP Dependency-Check: Setup, CI Integration & Report Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">OWASP Dependency-Check is a free, open-source SCA (Software Composition Analysis) tool that identifies known vulnerabilities in project dependencies by cross-referencing NVD CVE data. This guide covers installation, Maven/Gradle setup, CI integration, and false positive management.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Java, .NET, Node.js, Python, Go</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> NVD CVE database integration</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> HTML / XML / JSON / SARIF reports</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Works offline / air-gapped</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> 100% free and open-source</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What is OWASP Dependency-Check?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">OWASP Dependency-Check (DC) scans your project's libraries and compares them against the National Vulnerability Database (NVD) CVE feed. It supports Java JARs, .NET assemblies, npm packages, Python requirements files, and more. Because it stores the NVD data locally, it works in offline and air-gapped environments — a major advantage over cloud-based SaaS tools.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Installation</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">Three installation paths: standalone CLI, Maven plugin, or Gradle plugin.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Option 1: Standalone CLI (download zip from GitHub releases)
unzip dependency-check-*.zip
./dependency-check/bin/dependency-check.sh --version

# Option 2: Maven plugin (add to pom.xml)
# &lt;plugin&gt;
#   &lt;groupId&gt;org.owasp&lt;/groupId&gt;
#   &lt;artifactId&gt;dependency-check-maven&lt;/artifactId&gt;
#   &lt;version&gt;9.0.9&lt;/version&gt;
# &lt;/plugin&gt;

# Option 3: Homebrew (macOS/Linux)
brew install dependency-check</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Running a Scan</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># CLI scan with NVD API key
./dependency-check.sh \
  --project "MyApp" \
  --scan ./target/ \
  --format HTML \
  --nvdApiKey YOUR_NVD_API_KEY \
  --out ./reports/

# Maven: run as part of build
mvn dependency-check:check -DnvdApiKey=YOUR_KEY

# Maven: fail build on CVSS >= 7
mvn verify -DfailBuildOnCVSS=7 -DnvdApiKey=YOUR_KEY</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">HTML Report Walkthrough</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">The HTML report (dependency-check-report.html) contains three sections: a summary table of all scanned dependencies with their CVE counts, a detailed findings section with CPE identifiers and CVSS scores, and a suppressed findings section. Focus on the <strong>Critical</strong> and <strong>High</strong> rows first. Each row links to the NVD entry for full CVE details and available patches.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">CI/CD Integration — GitHub Actions</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>name: OWASP Dependency-Check

on: [push, pull_request]

jobs:
  dependency-check:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Run OWASP Dependency-Check
        uses: dependency-check/Dependency-Check_Action@main
        with:
          project: 'MyApp'
          path: '.'
          format: 'HTML'
          args: >
            --failOnCVSS 7
            --nvdApiKey &#123;&#123; secrets.NVD_API_KEY &#125;&#125;

      - name: Upload report
        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        if: always()
        with:
          name: dependency-check-report
          path: reports/</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">NVD API Key Setup</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Register for a free API key at <strong>nvd.nist.gov/developers/request-an-api-key</strong>. After registration you receive an email with the key. Without it, NVD updates are throttled at 5 requests/30 sec — the first update can take over an hour. With the key: 50 requests/30 sec, typically under 5 minutes.</p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Store the key as a CI secret (<code>NVD_API_KEY</code>) and pass it via <code>--nvdApiKey</code> flag or Maven property. Never hardcode it in pom.xml.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Suppression File for False Positives</h2>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;suppressions xmlns="https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-suppression.1.3.xsd"&gt;
  &lt;suppress&gt;
    &lt;notes&gt;CVE affects a code path not reachable in our app&lt;/notes&gt;
    &lt;cve&gt;CVE-2023-12345&lt;/cve&gt;
    &lt;gav regex="true"&gt;^com\.example:mylib:.*$&lt;/gav&gt;
  &lt;/suppress&gt;
&lt;/suppressions&gt;</code></pre>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Pass via <code>--suppression suppression.xml</code> (CLI) or <code>&lt;suppressionFile&gt;</code> (Maven). Always include a <code>&lt;notes&gt;</code> element explaining why the suppression is valid — it serves as your compliance audit trail.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">OWASP DC vs Snyk Comparison</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Aspect</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">OWASP DC</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Snyk</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Cost</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Free / OSS</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Free tier + paid</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Database</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">NVD (local copy)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Snyk curated DB</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Offline support</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Fix PRs</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border/50"><td class="py-2 pr-4">Container scanning</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">False positive rate</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Higher (needs tuning)</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">Lower</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />
  <FaqSection faqs={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
